            steps: `Begin your roast turkey adventure by preparing the bird for its flavour journey. Preheat your oven to 180°C (350°F). Ensure your turkey is fully thawed, then pat it dry with paper towels inside and out. This step is key for ensuring that deliciously crisp skin. <br><br>In a small bowl, mix together olive oil, melted butter, thyme, rosemary, garlic powder, onion powder, paprika, salt, and black pepper to create a flavour-packed rub. Carefully lift the skin over the turkey breast and massage half of the rub directly onto the meat under the skin. This will infuse the turkey with flavour from within, ensuring each bite is juicy and aromatic. Now, rub the remaining mixture all over the turkey's skin, paying special attention to the wings and legs. Let this sit for a few minutes to let the flavours meld. <br><br>Stuff the turkey cavity with a mix of quartered onions, chopped carrots, celery, halved lemon, and a handful of fresh parsley. These aromatic vegetables will steam inside the bird as it roasts, adding moisture and enhancing the flavour of the meat. If you're feeling adventurous, you can also add a few garlic cloves or sprigs of fresh thyme or rosemary. Tie the turkey legs together with kitchen twine to ensure even cooking, and tuck the wings under the bird to prevent them from burning. <br><br>Next, place the turkey breast-side up in a large roasting pan, making sure it’s sitting on a bed of the remaining chopped onions, carrots, and celery. This vegetable base will not only prevent the turkey from sticking to the pan but will also contribute to the rich, savoury gravy you'll make later. Pour the chicken stock and white wine into the bottom of the pan. This will create steam during the roasting process, keeping the turkey moist and adding depth to your gravy. <br><br>Cover the turkey loosely with aluminium foil to prevent the skin from browning too quickly. Place the turkey in the preheated oven and roast for about 3 to 4 hours, depending on the size of your bird (around 20 minutes per 500g). Every 30-40 minutes, baste the turkey with the juices that collect at the bottom of the pan. Basting helps the skin to crisp up and ensures the turkey stays moist. If you notice the skin browning too quickly, keep the foil on a little longer before removing it to let the skin crisp during the final hour of cooking. <br><br>About 30 minutes before the turkey is done, remove the foil to let the skin turn a gorgeous golden brown. The turkey is ready when the internal temperature reaches 75°C (165°F) in the thickest part of the thigh. To check, insert a meat thermometer into the thigh without touching the bone. Once it’s cooked to perfection, remove the turkey from the oven and allow it to rest for 20-30 minutes. Resting is crucial as it allows the juices to redistribute throughout the meat, making each slice moist and flavourful. <br><br>While the turkey rests, you can prepare the gravy. Pour the drippings from the roasting pan into a saucepan, skimming off excess fat. Place the roasting pan over medium heat, sprinkle in the flour, and whisk constantly, scraping up the delicious browned bits from the bottom of the pan. Slowly add the reserved drippings back into the pan along with some extra chicken stock, stirring until the gravy thickens to your liking. Season with salt and pepper to taste. <br><br>Once your turkey has rested, carve it carefully, starting with the legs and thighs before moving to the breast. Serve with a generous drizzle of the homemade gravy, along with your favourite sides like roasted vegetables or mashed potatoes. Each bite will be a perfect balance of crispy skin, tender meat, and savoury flavours. Happy feasting! `
